elve leading figures from Labour politics: Aneurin Bevan, Hugh Gaitskell, Harold Wilson, Barbara Castle, James Callaghan, Michael Foot, Tony Benn, Neil Kinnock, John Smith, Tony Blair, Gordon Brown and Ed Miliband. Each chapter explores how its subject attempted to use oratory to advance their agenda within the party and beyond. Students of British politics, Labour history and communication studies will find this volume essential reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical oratoryxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aPolitical oratoryxHistoryx21st centuryxGreat Britain. 0aPolitical oratoryzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical oratoryzGreat BritainxHistoryy21st century. 0aPoliticiansxBiographyxGreat Britain. 0aPoliticiansxLanguagexGreat Britain. 0aPoliticianszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aPoliticianszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoliticianszGreat BritainxLanguage. 0aPrime ministersxBiographyxGreat Britain. 0aPrime ministerszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aSocialismx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aSocialismzGreat Britainy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh  aAneurin Bevan.  aBarbara Castle.  aBritish politics.  aEd Miliband.  aGordon Brown.  aHarold Wilson.  aHugh Gaitskell.  aJames Callaghan.  aJohn Smith.  aLabour Party politics.  aMichael Foot.  aNeil Kinnock.  aParliamentary Party.  aTony Benn.  aTony Blair.  amedia engagement.  aoratorical skills.  aparty conference.  apublic engagement.  arhetorical techniques.1 aAtkins, Judi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennister, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrines, Andrew S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.